<L>Or &s;ends Commi&s;s'ners with credentials<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">The pa&s;&s;age that here follows is to be explained thus: In the year 1778, after the war had been raging three years, and the capture of Burgoyne's army was known in England, the Briti&s;h government con|cluded to give up all the objects for which the conte&s;t had been begun. It accordingly pa&s;&s;ed an act repealing all the acts of which the Ameri|cans complained, provided we would re&s;cind our declaration of Inde|pendence, and continue to be their colonies. The Mini&s;try then &s;ent over three Commi&s;&s;ioners, Mr. John&s;tone, Mr. Eden, and Lord Car|li&s;le. The&s;e commi&s;&s;ioners began their operations, and fini&s;hed them by attempting to bribe individuals among the members of the States, and of the army. This bait appears to have caught nobody but Arnold. The <HI>petticoated politition,</HI> here mentioned, is a woman of Philadelphia, (and a Lady of con&s;iderable di&s;tinction) through who&s;e agency they offered a bribe to Jo&s;eph Read, Governor of Penn&s;ylvania.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of promi&s;es and penitentials.</L>
